title: Directed Topoisomerase II activity disentangles interphase compartment domains
description: The topological state of the genome is controlled by the enzyme Topoisomerase II (Topo II) at different stages of the cell cycle. Topo II catalyzes double strand breaks to allow DNA duplexes to pass through one another. This strand passage activity is known to be important for decatenation of sister chromatids following S phase, for establishing mitotic chromosome folding, and for regulating DNA supercoiling upon transcriptional activation. In addition, Topo II localizes to CTCF binding sites at topologically associating domain (TAD) boundaries and is required for activation of facultative heterochromatin domains. Although Topo II is active throughout the cell cycle, recent studies have shown that interphase chromosomes are largely unentangled. In this study, we investigate the role of Topo II in chromosome entanglement and organization during mitosis and G1 entry. We show that unlike interphase chromosomes, mitotic chromosomes are highly entangled intrachromosomally at the 10-25 Megabase scale. In addition, Topo II activity is required for both compartment establishment at G1 entry and for strengthening compartments upon loss of cohesin mediated loop extrusion during G1. These changes in compartment strength are linked to Topo II mediated transitions in intrachromosomal entanglement.
